@d3 3
a5 7
Most so-called object-oriented languages such as Smalltalk, C$++$, Eiffel,
and the Eden Programming Language (EPL) have a concept of {\em
class}, which may be regarded as an object defining the behavior of
 a number of objects, i.e., its instances. 
\emd{} takes a different, more elegant approach to the
creation of objects. It provides a single general purpose way of constructing
objects:  the object constructor.
d9 3
a11 2
An object constructor defines the complete representation and operations of
a single object as well as its active behavior. Objects are created when an
d39 5
a43 8
\item{} Representation declarations
for data and processes that 
are contained in instances of the type.
\item{} A collection of operation signatures, where each operation
signature includes the name of the operation, and the number and 
types of the parameters of the operation.
\item{} A collection of operation bodies, i.e.,
the implementation for the previously specified operations.
d45 5
d51 34
a84 2
Further discussion of object constructors, and their usefulness in
(distributed) programming may be found in \cite{Hutchinson87}.
